4. GIT AS ITEM-LEVEL TEMPORAL DATABASE
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Every state change is committed to Git.
Each commit message contains the UUID of the affected item.
Structured commit messages encode:

    {ACTION} {TYPE}: {TITLE} | {CONTEXT} | Metadata: uuid:{UUID} {TAGS}

Actions: CREATED, UPDATED, RENAMED, DELETED
Types: NOTE, FILE, NOTEBOOK, SUBNOTEBOOK
Context: notebook path, parent information
Metadata: editor, line count, word count, file extension, tags

Complete item history is queryable via:

    git log --grep uuid:<UUID> --all
    git log --grep "DELETED.*<query>" --all
    git log --grep "RENAMED.*<query>" --all

Git operations are silent; user never interacts with Git directly.
Git is infrastructure, not interface.

5. EIGHT STRUCTURED COMMIT OPERATIONS
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The system generates eight distinct commit types, each with specific metadata:

CREATED NOTEBOOK
    - Notebook UUID, name, note count, file count, custom location flag
    - Initial structure commit

CREATED SUBNOTEBOOK
    - Subnotebook UUID, name, parent notebook
    - Nested hierarchy preservation

CREATED NOTE
    - Note UUID, title, notebook name, editor type (internal/vim)
    - Word count, line count, note type detection

CREATED FILE
    - File UUID, filename, extension, notebook name
    - Purpose detection from extension, line count

UPDATED NOTE
    - Note UUID, title, notebook name
    - Line changes (old → new, delta), word changes (old → new, delta)
    - Edit metrics for search and timeline

RENAMED NOTE/FILE
    - Item UUID, old name, new name, notebook name
    - Both names searchable forever

DELETED NOTE/FILE
    - Item UUID, title, notebook name, type
    - Item remains in history, removed from current view

DELETED SUBNOTEBOOK
    - Subnotebook UUID, name, parent notebook
    - Complete hierarchy preserved in history

All eight operations embed UUID in commit message.
All eight are searchable via git grep.
All eight contribute to temporal completeness.

6. GIT FILTER-REPO INTEGRATION FOR COMPLETE ERASURE
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
System includes full git-filter-repo integration for hard deletion:

import git_filter_repo

def _purge_with_filter_repo(self, repo_path, uuid):
    args = [
        "--force",
        "--path", "structure.json",
        "--invert-paths",
        "--grep", uuid
    ]
    git_filter_repo.main(args)
    subprocess.run(["git", "gc", "--aggressive", "--prune=now"])

This enables:
    - Complete removal of all traces of an item from Git history
    - Compliance with "right to be forgotten" (GDPR Article 17)
    - Permanent erasure when user requires it
    - Audit trail of erasure operation itself

Filter-repo is imported as module, not subprocess, enabling:
    - Progress reporting during long operations
    - Integration with UI feedback
    - Graceful fallback when filter-repo unavailable

7. COMPLETE GDPR COMPLIANCE THROUGH DUAL DELETE ARCHITECTURE
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
System implements two deletion modes with different compliance properties:

SOFT DELETE (FORGET)
    - Item removed from current view
    - Git commit with "DELETED" + UUID preserves history
