13. COMPLETE HIERARCHY RESURRECTION
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Deletion commits to Git; data is not removed (soft delete).
Search finds UUID of deleted item.
Commit before deletion is located via:

    git log --before <deletion_commit> --grep uuid:<UUID>

Full hierarchy is extracted from that commit:
    - structure.json at that point in time
    - notes.json and files.json at that point

Subnotebooks restored with all nested content:
    - Recursive collection of all notes and files
    - Complete preservation of parent-child relationships
    - All content from that historical moment

Temporary directory created with complete structure:
    - Minimal structure.json containing restored hierarchy
    - notes.json with all note content
    - files.json with all file content

One key press restores item to current structure:
    - UUID unchanged (permanent identity preserved)
    - Item reappears in current notebook
    - Git commit of restoration (CREATED event)
    - Temporal continuity preserved across deletion/resurrection

14. TIMELINE STATE RECONSTRUCTION
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Any item at any commit can be reconstructed via t command:

    git log --grep uuid:<UUID> --all --pretty=format:"%H|%ai|%s"

Each commit represents a version where the item changed.
Results sorted chronologically (newest first).

For any selected version:

    git show <commit_hash>:structure.json
    git show <commit_hash>:notes.json
    git show <commit_hash>:files.json

Recursive extraction preserves complete hierarchy:
    - If item is note → show note with context
    - If item is subnotebook → show entire subnotebook
    - If item is notebook → show complete notebook

Temporary directories isolate reconstructed state:
    - Read-only access ensures no accidental modification
    - Export available for file notes
    - Timeline navigation within historical context

Display mode indicates historical context:
    - Header shows "Historical: {title}"
    - Date from commit shown prominently
    - No edit/rename options (read-only)

Timeline shows evolution. Search shows existence.
Both use the same Git temporal database. Both are separate interfaces.

